 @Xer Kyubey  Yeah, I know how it works.  Sad thing is we're all capable of falling for such folly.  Think of how many things people believe that are technically nothing but "academic" answers.   Things that are certainly true in some way, or true if certain assumptions are made.  Such concepts can be technically true but functionally they can be completely wrong.

I had this problem when I was younger...falling for the fallacy of technically correct, academic answers.  A lot of otherwise intelligent people think "Well it's technically correct for a start, and some other stuff SEEMS reasonable, so I'll just accept it"  Take the fact that oil will run out at some point...technically very correct.  Yet people have predicted the demise of the oil industry "within 20 years" for the last 120 years or so.  The guy that wrote "The population bomb"...a technically correct concept (there is a limit to the number of people that can live on the planet) but functionally wrong as advances in agriculture have outstripped population growth.

The case for extreme anthropogenic global warming is 100% academic...indeed, its a whole pile of academic answers, each of which not only likely has the normal flaws of academic answers but which also depends on the other aspects being true.  At some point, you have to actually check the facts and compare them to the reality.

